In the South, we have meat & 3s: Country-style restaurants where the food is cheap, the setting is simple (you can fit in wearing anything from church clothes to a fluorescent-yellow work vest) and the atmosphere is friendly — as long as you don’t slow a waitress down.
A 'meat & 3' place typically offers homey desserts like pies or cobblers.
Most meat & 3s are only open for breakfast and lunch, though breakfast is sometimes served all day and lunch usually starts at 11 a.m.
The menu will be laminated (easier to wipe off) or folded paper.
Fried chicken, collard greens, mashed potatoes and corn bread are staples of ‘meat & 3’ restaurants.
The correct meat & 3 dessert: The daily flavor of cobbler.

Capt. Aaron Aaron and a group of friends put up a cross as a memorial to their friend, Capt. Richard Baran, who disappeared while hunting in the Hatteras Inlet in North Carolina in January 2016. A few months later Aaron built the cross and put it up. It was lost in a storm and wound up in Fort Lauderdale in February 2019, Aaron and Baran’s sister, Robin Stowe, said.
Capt. Aaron Aaron put the cross he built as a memorial to friend Rich Baran on board his boat to transport it to an island in North Carolina after Baran disappeared in January 2016.

Mollie Wilmot, her pool, and the freighter Mercedes I, which spent 105 days stuck in the back yard of her Palm Beach mansion. The ship washed ashore Nov. 23, 1984, during a three-day storm. It eventually was towed off and was sunk in March 1985 as an artificial reef off Oakland Park Boulevard in Broward County.
A grand piano is seen on a sandbar in Biscayne Bay on January 26, 2011 in Miami, Florida. The piano was charred from being burned.

North Carolina Museum of Art’s Statue of Bacchus is scanned with technology from Scansite to see intricate details and give conservators a better look into how to conserve the statue on Tuesday, Jan. 9, 2018. The project, on hold since the 1960s while technology was being developed, aims to deconstruct Bacchus into a beautifully preserved ancient torso. The head, newly freed torso, and re-creation of Bacchus will be displayed along with digital experiences to engage the public in the conservation process.

United States Marine Corps recruits of Charlie Company, 1st Recruit Training Battalion, run through an obstacle course Sept. 15, 2017, on Parris Island, S.C. The Crucible is the final test a recruit must pass before earning the Eagle Globe and Anchor emblem. Charlie Company is scheduled to graduate Sept. 22, 2017. Parris Island has been the site of Marine Corps recruit training since Nov. 1, 1915. Today, approximately 19,000 recruits come to Parris Island annually for the chance to become United States Marines by enduring 12 weeks of rigorous, transformative training. Parris Island is home to entry-level enlisted training for 49 percent of male recruits and 100 percent of female recruits in the Marine Corps. (U.S. Marine Corps photo by Lance Cpl. Joseph Jacob)

Division of Motor Vehicles mapped the homes of the more than 500 people who work at the DMV’s headquarters on New Bern Avenue in Raleigh and compared it with two sites it considered for a new headquarters. The state Division of Motor Vehicles has long been located on New Bern Avenue, east of downtown Raleigh. Now, the DMV has plans to move hundreds of workers and its headquarters to Rocky Mount.

In this May 7, 1973 file photo, reporters Bob Woodward, right, and Carl Bernstein, whose reporting of the Watergate case won them a Pulitzer Prize, sit in the newsroom of the Washington Post in Washington. More than 40 years after they became the world’s most famous journalism duo, Bob Woodward and Carl Bernstein are still making news. Bernstein was among three CNN reporters who last week broke the story of former Donald Trump lawyer Michael Cohen’s allegation that Trump had advance knowledge of the June 2016 meeting between representatives of his campaign and Russian officials. On Tuesday, July 31, 2018, Woodward’s upcoming “Fear: Inside the Trump White House” was No. 1 on Amazon.com. (AP Photo, File)

Copies of Bob Woodward’s “Fear” are seen for sale at Costco, Wednesday, Sept. 11, 2018 in Arlington, Va. It’s not clear whether President Donald Trump has much to fear from “Fear” itself. In the South, we have meat & 3s: Country-style restaurants where the food is cheap, the setting is simple (you can fit in wearing anything from church clothes to a fluorescent-yellow work vest) and the atmosphere is friendly — as long as you don’t slow a waitress down.
A 'meat & 3' place typically offers homey desserts like pies or cobblers.
Most meat & 3s are only open for breakfast and lunch, though breakfast is sometimes served all day and lunch usually starts at 11 a.m.
The menu will be laminated (easier to wipe off) or folded paper.
Fried chicken, collard greens, mashed potatoes and corn bread are staples of ‘meat & 3’ restaurants.
The correct meat & 3 dessert: The daily flavor of cobbler.

Capt. Aaron Aaron and a group of friends put up a cross as a memorial to their friend, Capt. Richard Baran, who disappeared while hunting in the Hatteras Inlet in North Carolina in January 2016. A few months later Aaron built the cross and put it up. It was lost in a storm and wound up in Fort Lauderdale in February 2019, Aaron and Baran’s sister, Robin Stowe, said.
Capt. Aaron Aaron put the cross he built as a memorial to friend Rich Baran on board his boat to transport it to an island in North Carolina after Baran disappeared in January 2016.

Mollie Wilmot, her pool, and the freighter Mercedes I, which spent 105 days stuck in the back yard of her Palm Beach mansion. The ship washed ashore Nov. 23, 1984, during a three-day storm. It eventually was towed off and was sunk in March 1985 as an artificial reef off Oakland Park Boulevard in Broward County.

United States Marine Corps recruits of Charlie Company, 1st Recruit Training Battalion, run through an obstacle course Sept. 15, 2017, on Parris Island, S.C. The Crucible is the final test a recruit must pass before earning the Eagle Globe and Anchor emblem. Charlie Company is scheduled to graduate Sept. 22, 2017. Parris Island has been the site of Marine Corps recruit training since Nov. 1, 1915. Today, approximately 19,000 recruits come to Parris Island annually for the chance to become United States Marines by enduring 12 weeks of rigorous, transformative training. Parris Island is home to entry-level enlisted training for 49 percent of male recruits and 100 percent of female recruits in the Marine Corps. (U.S. Marine Corps photo by Lance Cpl. Joseph Jacob)

The N.C. Division of Motor Vehicles mapped the homes of the more than 500 people who work at the DMV’s headquarters on New Bern Avenue in Raleigh and compared it with two sites it considered for a new headquarters. The Council of State will consider approving a lease for Site A, in Rocky Mount, which had the cheapest rent of the dozen proposals the DMV received but would require a longer drive for most of the employees.
The state Division of Motor Vehicles has long been located on New Bern Avenue, east of downtown Raleigh. Now, the DMV has plans to move hundreds of workers and its headquarters to Rocky Mount.

In this May 7, 1973 file photo, reporters Bob Woodward, right, and Carl Bernstein, whose reporting of the Watergate case won them a Pulitzer Prize, sit in the newsroom of the Washington Post in Washington. More than 40 years after they became the world’s most famous journalism duo, Bob Woodward and Carl Bernstein are still making news. Bernstein was among three CNN reporters who last week broke the story of former Donald Trump lawyer Michael Cohen’s allegation that Trump had advance knowledge of the June 2016 meeting between representatives of his campaign and Russian officials. On Tuesday, July 31, 2018, Woodward’s upcoming “Fear: Inside the Trump White House” was No. 1 on Amazon.com. (AP Photo, File)

Copies of Bob Woodward’s “Fear” are seen for sale at Costco, Wednesday, Sept. 11, 2018 in Arlington, Va. It’s not clear whether President Donald Trump has much to fear from “Fear” itself. But the book of that name has set off a yes-no war between author Bob Woodward and the president, using all the assets they can muster.
Author and journalist Bob Woodward

Hundreds of people participated in the Women’s March on Raleigh on Saturday, Jan. 26, 2019. The march took participants around the NC legislative building and onto Halifax Mall for a rally with performers and speakers.
People cross the bridge connecting Halifax Mall and the NC legislative building to attend the Women’s March on Raleigh’s rally on Saturday, Jan. 26, 2019.
Women’s March on Raleigh participants cross the bridge connecting the NC legislative building to Halifax Mall on Saturday, Jan. 26, 2019.

Takiyah Thompson, one of the emcees of the Women’s March on Raleigh, speaks to the crowd about being accosted by police for having a flag with a stick attached to it as she entered Halifax Mall on Saturday, Jan. 26, 2019. Thompson pointed out that barely anyone in the marching crowd stopped to help her.
